Northcott Medulloblastoma: Group differences in LV expression

J. Taroni and C. Greene 2018

In this notebook, we’ll plot the differences in PLIER latent variable expression between the three subgroups: SHH, Group 3, and Group 4.

Our objective is to learn about melting wide data, wrangling data, and using ggplot2 along the way.

First, a note on tidy data

In order to use ggplot2, we’ll need the data in “long” or “tidy” format. PLIER outputs what we want to plot in what we call “wide” format.

Read more about tidy data here.

To quote from Hadley Wickham’s R for Data Science:

There are three interrelated rules which make a dataset tidy: * Each variable must have its own column. * Each observation must have its own row. * Each value must have its own cell.

Let’s look at a toy example.

set.seed(12345)
toy_df <- data.frame( 
  cbind(c("GENEA", "GENEB", "GENEC"),
        matrix(rnorm(30), ncol = 10))
)
colnames(toy_df) <- c("Gene", paste0("Sample", 1:10))

toy_df is now in “wide” format.

toy_df

Let’s get it into “long” format.

toy_long_df <- reshape2::melt(toy_df, id.vars = "Gene", 
                              variable.name = "Sample", 
                              value.name = "Expression")
attributes are not identical across measure variables; they will be dropped
toy_long_df

Let’s remove these toy examples from the workspace.

rm(toy_df, toy_long_df)

Read in data

Sample metadata

We’ll use the sample metadata, which contains the subgroup information, in our plotting.

sample_meta_df <- readr::read_tsv(metadata_file)
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  source_name = col_character(),
  sample_identifier = col_character(),
  tissue_type = col_character(),
  age = col_character(),
  histology = col_character(),
  sex = col_character(),
  subgroup = col_character()
)

PLIER model

plier_results <- readr::read_rds(plier_file)

We’ll focus on the significant (FDR < 0.05 and AUC > 0.75) latent variables for now. Let’s get the indices of those LVs.

sig_summary_df <- plier_results$summary %>%
  dplyr::filter(FDR < 0.05,
                AUC > 0.75)
sig_index <- unique(sig_summary_df$`LV index`)

Let’s get the B matrix out of plier_results and filter it to only the significant LVs.

b_matrix <- plier_results$B
sig_b_matrix <- b_matrix[as.integer(sig_index), ]
# add LV column
sig_b_wide <- tibble::rownames_to_column(as.data.frame(sig_b_matrix), 
                                         var = "LV")

Tidy

Let’s look at what format this is in currently.

sig_b_wide[1:5, 1:5]

We want this in long format. We’ll use reshape2::melt to do this just like in the toy example above.

sig_b_df <- reshape2::melt(sig_b_wide, id.vars = "LV", variable.name = "Sample",
                           value.name = "Expression_level")
head(sig_b_df)

Let’s add the sample metadata to this data.frame with inner_join.

b_df <- inner_join(x = sig_b_df, y = sample_meta_df, 
                   by = c("Sample" = "source_name"))
Column `Sample`/`source_name` joining factor and character vector, coercing into character vector
head(b_df)

Plotting

For illustrative purposes, we’ll pick an LV and go through using ggplot2 to make a plot.

lv <- "94,IRIS_Monocyte-Day7"

First, let’s filter the data.frame to only observations of LV 94.

lv94_df <- b_df %>% 
  dplyr::filter(LV == lv)

Boxplot

Let’s make a boxplot, using the subgroups as groups. We’ll use defaults and then tweak different things one by one, so you can see how different functions and arguments work.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Let’s add individual points with geom_jitter.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter()

Let’s make the points more transparent by setting alpha and narrow the width of the jitter with width

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter(width = 0.175, alpha = 0.5)

Let’s change the theme to something more suitable for publication.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter(width = 0.175, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add built in theme
  theme_classic()

Let’s add labels and a title with the labs function.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter(width = 0.175, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add built in theme
  theme_classic() +
  labs(x = "Subgroup", y = "LV Expression", title = "LV94 Macrophages")

Let’s center the title and make it bold with theme and element_text.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter(width = 0.175, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add built in theme
  theme_classic() +
  labs(x = "Subgroup", y = "LV Expression", title = "LV94 Macrophages") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"))

Let’s put the x-axis labels on a 45 degree angle with theme.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they

  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1, angle = 45))

Let’s get rid of the legend since it’s redundant.

lv94_df %>%

Let’s use colors that are consistent with our clustering notebook with scale_color_manual.

Stats

Let’s do a pairwise Wilcoxon rank sum test and put that information onto the plot.

pairwise.wilcox.test(x = lv94_df$Expression_level, g = lv94_df$subgroup,
                     p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

    Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 

data:  lv94_df$Expression_level and lv94_df$subgroup 

        Group 3 Group 4
Group 4 0.00041 -      
SHH     3.7e-05 0.00047

P value adjustment method: bonferroni

We’ll use the package ggsignif to add this information. This will automatically do the tests and add the p-values to the plot, but we have more control over how the test is done if we do things manually.

lv94_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subgroup, y = Expression_level, 
             group = subgroup, colour = subgroup)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # we remove outlier points because they
  # will be included in the jitter
  geom_jitter(width = 0.175, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add built in theme
  theme_classic() +
  labs(x = "Subgroup", y = "LV Expression", title = "LV94 Macrophages") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1, angle = 45),
        legend.position = "none") +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("#FFC125", "#00CD66", "#00BFFF")) +
  geom_signif(y_position = c(1.3, 1.6, 1.9), 
              xmin = c("Group 3", "Group 3", "Group 4"), 
              xmax = c("Group 4", "SHH", "SHH"),
              annotation = c("0.00041", "3.7e-05", "0.00047"), 
              tip_length = 0, color = "black")
